00:02:21.570 --> 00:02:24.570
You were an editor
and you were a writer,

00:02:24.570 --> 00:02:27.320
what influence did
your years there have

00:02:27.320 --> 00:02:29.560
on your own evolution as a writer?

00:02:29.560 --> 00:02:30.890
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard:
Well, I always say

00:02:30.890 --> 00:02:36.410
that my real education actually
happened at National Geographic.

00:02:36.410 --> 00:02:40.980
I learned so much about
storytelling, about the fact

00:02:40.980 --> 00:02:44.960
that the world is full
of fascinating people,

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:48.390
fascinating events and stories.

00:02:48.390 --> 00:02:53.560 position:56%
But most of all, I learned about
research and I learned that you need

00:02:53.560 --> 00:02:58.320
to dig deeply, you need to
take the time to understand it,

00:02:58.320 --> 00:03:02.870
and you need to find the people
who really know the subject

00:03:02.870 --> 00:03:04.750
that you are going to look into.

00:03:04.750 --> 00:03:08.910
You know, at National Geographic,
you could be working on something

00:03:08.910 --> 00:03:13.690 position:56%
about meerkats one day and then
something about a river another day.

00:03:13.690 --> 00:03:15.690
So it really fluctuated.

00:03:15.690 --> 00:03:20.820
And so-- But the one
consistent thing throughout is

00:03:20.820 --> 00:03:23.940
that there's always somebody
who knows the subject

00:03:23.940 --> 00:03:27.440
and knows it really, really
well and have spent most of his

00:03:27.440 --> 00:03:30.760
or her life studying it and
you need to find that person

00:03:30.760 --> 00:03:35.210
and make him your friend.

00:03:35.210 --> 00:03:36.760
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: When
and how did it come to you

00:03:36.760 --> 00:03:40.070
that you should try to write
what became "The River of Doubt".

00:03:40.070 --> 00:03:41.370
You were young.

00:03:41.370 --> 00:03:43.410
You were not a trained historian.

00:03:43.410 --> 00:03:46.240
The subject involved
travel to a dangerous place,

00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:48.900
dealings with languages
other than your own.

00:03:48.900 --> 00:03:50.920
Tell us about the challenges
and apprehensions

00:03:50.920 --> 00:03:54.050
that confronted you
when you started out.

00:03:54.050 --> 00:03:57.160
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard: So I first
heard the story, I was having lunch

00:03:57.160 --> 00:04:01.810
with a friend of mine, James
Chase, who wrote the book "1912".

00:04:01.810 --> 00:04:03.110
Did you know?

00:04:03.110 --> 00:04:06.570 position:56%
And a really-- an extraordinary man,
and this is the election, you know,

00:04:06.570 --> 00:04:09.270
the Bull Moose election
where Roosevelt tried

00:04:09.270 --> 00:04:11.100
to regain the presidency and lost.

00:04:11.100 --> 00:04:16.060
And he said, "Have you heard about
this trip that Roosevelt took

00:04:16.060 --> 00:04:18.370
in the Amazon after that election?"

00:04:18.370 --> 00:04:21.080
And I had read about Theodore
Roosevelt, I was interested in him.

00:04:21.080 --> 00:04:23.930
But because it's after his
active political career,

00:04:23.930 --> 00:04:25.490
it was sort of glossed over.

00:04:25.490 --> 00:04:27.000
And I started researching it,

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:28.930
actually went back to
National Geographic.

00:04:28.930 --> 00:04:30.620
They have a great library there,

00:04:30.620 --> 00:04:33.570
and then went to the
Library of Congress.

00:04:33.570 --> 00:04:37.860
And I was stunned because, you
know, there is murder, drowning.

00:04:37.860 --> 00:04:40.190
You know, they left the
murder and the rainforest.

00:04:40.190 --> 00:04:41.830
Roosevelt nearly took his own life.

00:04:41.830 --> 00:04:46.130
It's set in the Amazon, the
richest ecosystem on earth,

00:04:46.130 --> 00:04:49.100
something I would love
to write about.

00:04:49.100 --> 00:04:52.600
And so, I was just
hooked right away.

00:04:52.600 --> 00:04:55.870
But it is daunting to take
on Theodore Roosevelt,

00:04:55.870 --> 00:04:57.830
to take on the Amazon, but--

00:04:57.830 --> 00:04:59.270 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: Take on a book.

00:04:59.270 --> 00:05:00.570
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard: Right.

00:05:00.570 --> 00:05:02.820
To take on a book, exactly.

00:05:02.820 --> 00:05:07.920
But I was really excited about it
because I knew that to a writer,

00:05:07.920 --> 00:05:11.300
this is just a gift, it
had so much to work with.

00:05:11.300 --> 00:05:14.360
And I, thanks to my years
at National Geographic,

00:05:14.360 --> 00:05:15.880
I knew how to do research.

00:05:15.880 --> 00:05:19.210
That was the only thing
that I was confident about.

00:05:19.210 --> 00:05:20.830
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: But you,
you went to the Amazon, right?

00:05:20.830 --> 00:05:22.130
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard: I did.

00:05:22.130 --> 00:05:26.100
I did. I went to this river,
which is still incredibly remote.

00:05:26.100 --> 00:05:32.150
I did some research in Rio and
then I went to this little town

00:05:32.150 --> 00:05:35.270
in northwestern Brazil
called Porto Velho.

00:05:35.270 --> 00:05:40.090
I rented a plane, I hired a
pilot, and I flew for hours

00:05:40.090 --> 00:05:44.710
