00:07:12.010 --> 00:07:15.690
What, if any, common elements
drew you to their stories?

00:07:15.690 --> 00:07:16.990
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard:
So, what interest me,

00:07:16.990 --> 00:07:18.340
and we were talking
about this earlier.

00:07:18.340 --> 00:07:22.200
I loved to read biographies,
but as a writer,

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:28.220
I like to tell a tighter story,
a more sort of personal story

00:07:28.220 --> 00:07:33.480
where I can spend five years really
focusing and digging in deep.

00:07:33.480 --> 00:07:39.200
And I-- I'm looking for a story
that I hope is eliminating

00:07:39.200 --> 00:07:43.110
about the person and about
the time in which they live.

00:07:43.110 --> 00:07:47.020
And specifically what interest me,
I think that often when we look

00:07:47.020 --> 00:07:49.160
at history, we're kind of drawn

00:07:49.160 --> 00:07:55.510
to the big public moments
of triumph or of infamy.

00:07:55.510 --> 00:08:01.260
But what interest me are the
more private moments of struggle

00:08:01.260 --> 00:08:07.000
when someone is sick like
James Garfield or terrified

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:11.890
like Theodore Roosevelt, or
desperate like Winston Churchill,

00:08:11.890 --> 00:08:15.050
and searching for a
foothold and uncertain.

00:08:15.050 --> 00:08:20.200
And I think it's in those moments,
and it's true for all of us.

00:08:20.200 --> 00:08:23.260 position:56%
This is something that we all
share, that we share with these sort

00:08:23.260 --> 00:08:25.860
of great historical
figures is that that's

00:08:25.860 --> 00:08:29.830 position:56%
