00:12:08.430 --> 00:12:12.610
that I understand this event
much better because of it.

00:12:12.610 --> 00:12:15.200
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: One
thing about the late 19th

00:12:15.200 --> 00:12:18.610
and early 20th centuries,
Churchill [inaudible] in his memoir

00:12:18.610 --> 00:12:23.440
"My Early Years" is that
it's really a lost world.

00:12:23.440 --> 00:12:26.640
It's the period when the
world began to change

00:12:26.640 --> 00:12:30.180
in incredibly dramatic ways,
even more than it's changing now

00:12:30.180 --> 00:12:32.450
because you literally went
from the horse and buggy

00:12:32.450 --> 00:12:33.750
to the car to the airplane--

00:12:33.750 --> 00:12:35.050
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard: Right, right.

00:12:35.050 --> 00:12:36.350
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley:
-- in that period.

00:12:36.350 --> 00:12:37.650
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard: Right, and
that's another thing actually

00:12:37.650 --> 00:12:42.070
that interest me about because
the world was changing so quickly

00:12:42.070 --> 00:12:44.140
in every conceivable way.

00:12:44.140 --> 00:12:46.950
But also our knowledge
of the world, you know,

00:12:46.950 --> 00:12:51.050
this is sort of the gilded age
of exploration, you know, and--

00:12:51.050 --> 00:12:54.280
And so that too is
absolutely fascinating

00:12:54.280 --> 00:12:56.620
and Churchill was right
in the middle of that.

00:12:56.620 --> 00:12:57.920
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: Right.

00:12:57.920 --> 00:13:00.930
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard: He's right on
the cusp of this incredible change,

00:13:00.930 --> 00:13:04.270
and it's fascinating to
see it through his eyes.

00:13:04.270 --> 00:13:07.080
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: A couple
of things that are connected,

00:13:07.080 --> 00:13:09.580
you write as Churchill escaped
the Boer prisoner of war camp

00:13:09.580 --> 00:13:11.670
and faced dangerous
challenges, quote here,

00:13:11.670 --> 00:13:16.610
would be a grand adventure, an
exploit of a most romantic kind.

00:13:16.610 --> 00:13:19.290
The notion of British
ideas of wars as--

00:13:19.290 --> 00:13:23.420
war as romance is a strong
undercurrent in your book.

00:13:23.420 --> 00:13:26.890
And William Manchester in his
introduction to Churchill's memoir

00:13:26.890 --> 00:13:30.150
of "My Early Years" says that
his experiences in India and then

00:13:30.150 --> 00:13:33.310
in South Africa led him
to see "the glorification

00:13:33.310 --> 00:13:35.190
of war for the fraud it was".

00:13:35.190 --> 00:13:39.010
Do you agree with that judgment?

00:13:39.010 --> 00:13:40.310
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard: Yeah, I do.

00:13:40.310 --> 00:13:43.790
It's-- You know, at that time, the
British Empire was huge, you know,

00:13:43.790 --> 00:13:47.300
ruled 450 million people,
a quarter of the population

00:13:47.300 --> 00:13:49.410
and they were spread
all over the world.

00:13:49.410 --> 00:13:51.610
And so they were spread very thin.

00:13:51.610 --> 00:13:54.880
You know, they are constantly
putting down, putting down revolts.

00:13:54.880 --> 00:13:59.200 position:56%
But to them, you know, these little
colonial wars that they would fight,

00:13:59.200 --> 00:14:02.520
it was all about gallantry,
you know, and being dashing

00:14:02.520 --> 00:14:05.660
and they hated losing
their red coats.

00:14:05.660 --> 00:14:09.010
You know, they thought the khakis
made them look like bus drivers

00:14:09.010 --> 00:14:13.300
and they were still even, you know,
for the Boer War, when it began,

00:14:13.300 --> 00:14:16.270
they were still fighting in
these perfect precise lines.

00:14:16.270 --> 00:14:19.030 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: So the Boer War
really was a prelude to World War I.

00:14:19.030 --> 00:14:20.330
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard:
It absolutely was.

00:14:20.330 --> 00:14:23.900
It was the beginning of modern
warfare and I think, you know,

00:14:23.900 --> 00:14:27.210
not that many Americans especially
know much about the Boer War

00:14:27.210 --> 00:14:30.080
but it was some of the
first guerilla fighting,

00:14:30.080 --> 00:14:34.190 position:56%
it was the first concentration
camps, the modernization of weapons,

00:14:34.190 --> 00:14:37.610
and all of those things
that the British Army going

00:14:37.610 --> 00:14:40.440
in was completely different from
the British Army coming out.

00:14:40.440 --> 00:14:44.300
And it prepared them
for World War I.

00:14:44.300 --> 00:14:45.600
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: Right.

00:14:45.600 --> 00:14:49.010
You're right really splendidly
about the Boers people whom most

00:14:49.010 --> 00:14:51.640
of us know are about
whom we know very little.

00:14:51.640 --> 00:14:54.860
Is the Boer presence in South
Africa still very strong?

00:14:54.860 --> 00:14:56.160
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard: Well, they--

00:14:56.160 --> 00:15:00.800
obviously the prelude to the
Afrikaners and fortunately,

00:15:00.800 --> 00:15:02.230
things are changing a lot.

00:15:02.230 --> 00:15:06.190
You know, the Boers
were interesting people.

00:15:06.190 --> 00:15:10.280
They were very independent,
they're very religious,

00:15:10.280 --> 00:15:12.210
and they were unabashedly racist.

00:15:12.210 --> 00:15:15.290 position:56%
And, you know, that's sort of what--

00:15:15.290 --> 00:15:17.210
And you may have heard
of the great track or--

00:15:17.210 --> 00:15:20.730
and the 1835 they moved from
the Cape hundreds of miles

00:15:20.730 --> 00:15:25.050
into the interior and that was
set up primarily by the fact

00:15:25.050 --> 00:15:28.880
that two years earlier the British
Empire had abolished slavery.

00:15:28.880 --> 00:15:34.560
And so even though the British
Empire promised people in Africa,

00:15:34.560 --> 00:15:38.060
native Africans and the Indian
population that was living there,

00:15:38.060 --> 00:15:40.230
that as soon as they won the war,

00:15:40.230 --> 00:15:42.850
things would change
and be better for them.

00:15:42.850 --> 00:15:48.640 position:56%
As we all know, that took much
longer than anyone would have hoped.

00:15:48.640 --> 00:15:54.590 position:56%
And so, of course, there is still
an Afrikaner presence but, you know,

00:15:54.590 --> 00:15:58.520
obviously Nelson Mandela was
a huge breaking point for that

00:15:58.520 --> 00:15:59.820 position:56%
and things have changed quite a bit.

00:15:59.820 --> 00:16:02.660
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: Tell us
a little bit about Churchill.

00:16:02.660 --> 00:16:05.700
I-- he did change his--

00:16:05.700 --> 00:16:09.050
The experience in South Africa did
change him, but I kept thinking

00:16:09.050 --> 00:16:11.650
as I was reading your book
that a perfectly apt title

00:16:11.650 --> 00:16:13.150
for it would have been
"Naked Ambition".

00:16:13.150 --> 00:16:14.450
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard: Yeah.

00:16:14.450 --> 00:16:15.750
Absolutely.

00:16:15.750 --> 00:16:19.830
He was just a bundle
of burning ambition.

00:16:19.830 --> 00:16:22.000
That was the one description

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.290
of him that's absolutely
true throughout his life.

00:16:24.290 --> 00:16:25.590
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley:
You think that that--

00:16:25.590 --> 00:16:29.480
you think that that is traceable
to his feelings about his father?

00:16:29.480 --> 00:16:31.040
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard: Some
of it I think it was--

00:16:31.040 --> 00:16:33.450 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: Because, you
know, naked ambition in well to do--

00:16:33.450 --> 00:16:36.530
of course they weren't rich in
the British-- but prominent.

00:16:36.530 --> 00:16:39.040
Naked ambition is not that
really all that competent

00:16:39.040 --> 00:16:40.400
in that particular class.

00:16:40.400 --> 00:16:41.780
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard:
It's looked down upon.

00:16:41.780 --> 00:16:43.080
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: Yeah.

00:16:43.080 --> 00:16:44.380
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard:
It's looked down upon.

00:16:44.380 --> 00:16:45.680
And I've always felt that
that was the American in him.

00:16:45.680 --> 00:16:50.970
His mother, the beautiful socialite
Jennie Jerome was American.

00:16:50.970 --> 00:16:56.050
And he-- and in fact he told his
mother, this is a pushing age

00:16:56.050 --> 00:16:57.350
and we must push with the best.

00:16:57.350 --> 00:16:58.650
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: Right, right.

00:16:58.650 --> 00:16:59.950
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard: And so
he-- She was very connected.

00:16:59.950 --> 00:17:03.110
She had all these powerful
men who adored her.

00:17:03.110 --> 00:17:06.350
And so he was always having
her, you know, help me out here,

00:17:06.350 --> 00:17:08.430
have this person get
me an assignment.

00:17:08.430 --> 00:17:10.330
Because he was always
throwing himself into wars

00:17:10.330 --> 00:17:14.750
because he thought that's the
best way for me to win fame

00:17:14.750 --> 00:17:17.290
and propel myself to
political power.

00:17:17.290 --> 00:17:20.600
And he called it the glittering
gateway to distinction.

00:17:20.600 --> 00:17:21.900
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: Right.

00:17:21.900 --> 00:17:26.320
You quoted the famous remark
by his first love, Pamela--

00:17:26.320 --> 00:17:27.620
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard: Plowden.

00:17:27.620 --> 00:17:28.920
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: -- Plowden.

00:17:28.920 --> 00:17:30.720
Who said, when you first meet
Winston and you see all the things

00:17:30.720 --> 00:17:32.830
that are wrong with him, and
once you get to know him,

00:17:32.830 --> 00:17:34.540
you see all the things
that are right with him.

00:17:34.540 --> 00:17:35.840
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard:
Yeah, that's right.

00:17:35.840 --> 00:17:37.140
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: What
was wrong, what was right,

00:17:37.140 --> 00:17:38.870
and as you came to know him?

00:17:38.870 --> 00:17:40.240
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard:
Well, so what was wrong,

00:17:40.240 --> 00:17:44.970 position:56%
he's obviously not only ambitious
but incredibly, incredibly arrogant.

00:17:44.970 --> 00:17:46.270
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: Right.

00:17:46.270 --> 00:17:47.570
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard: And that
is probably to throughout--

00:17:47.570 --> 00:17:48.870
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley:
And self-indulgent.

00:17:48.870 --> 00:17:50.170
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard: Through--
And throughout his life.

00:17:50.170 --> 00:17:52.210
It was absolutely all
about, about him.

00:17:52.210 --> 00:17:56.890
In fact, I found it entertaining
because again and again and again

00:17:56.890 --> 00:18:00.390
in letters and journals and
different newspaper articles,

00:18:00.390 --> 00:18:02.440
people would say you know

00:18:02.440 --> 00:18:05.580
that Winston Churchill,
I cannot stand the kid.

00:18:05.580 --> 00:18:08.760
He's going to be prime minister
one day but he drives me crazy.

00:18:08.760 --> 00:18:10.060
And--

00:18:10.060 --> 00:18:12.020
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: A very
amusing, a very amusing story

00:18:12.020 --> 00:18:14.450
that she tells us while
he was in prison

00:18:14.450 --> 00:18:17.200
in South Africa, he
