00:21:13.050 --> 00:21:16.620
And, you know, I know
a lot of historians.

00:21:16.620 --> 00:21:19.830
I read a lot of academic
histories and I respect them.

00:21:19.830 --> 00:21:21.130
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: Right.

00:21:21.130 --> 00:21:22.430
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard:
It's just not what I do.

00:21:22.430 --> 00:21:25.970
And I hope that it's actually
a collaborative thing.

00:21:25.970 --> 00:21:27.770
You know, I hope that
there are people who--

00:21:27.770 --> 00:21:30.260
And a lot of people I've
met, you say, you know,

00:21:30.260 --> 00:21:31.980
I thought I hated history.

00:21:31.980 --> 00:21:34.120
I was never interested in history.

00:21:34.120 --> 00:21:36.420
And then I read something
by David McCullough

00:21:36.420 --> 00:21:38.290
or Antony Beevor and I was hooked.

00:21:38.290 --> 00:21:42.120
And a lot of times they say, and
it made me want to know more.

00:21:42.120 --> 00:21:45.070
And so then I started
to read more deeply.

00:21:45.070 --> 00:21:48.830
And I-- So I hope that in a way
there's a conduit for people

00:21:48.830 --> 00:21:51.630
who think that they don't
like history to realize--

00:21:51.630 --> 00:21:55.080
Actually they do and there
are these fascinating stories

00:21:55.080 --> 00:21:57.630
