00:29:08.240 --> 00:29:10.980
&gt;&gt; You made a brief reference
to the British policy

00:29:10.980 --> 00:29:15.120
of concentration camps in the
Boer War, which was really one

00:29:15.120 --> 00:29:19.180
of the most shameful episodes
in the British Empire's history,

00:29:19.180 --> 00:29:22.870
particularly its impact
on women and children

00:29:22.870 --> 00:29:26.030
and mother and noncombatants.

00:29:26.030 --> 00:29:32.890
Did Churchill ever acknowledge that
or did that affect him in any way?

00:29:32.890 --> 00:29:34.950
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard: Well,
it-- what affected him--

00:29:34.950 --> 00:29:38.370
and I don't know this but--
was his own imprisonment.

00:29:38.370 --> 00:29:39.670
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley: Right.

00:29:39.670 --> 00:29:41.260
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard: And
it affected him deeply.

00:29:41.260 --> 00:29:43.640
And he never forgot it.

00:29:43.640 --> 00:29:47.130
And even though it was completely
on the other end of the spectrum

00:29:47.130 --> 00:29:49.850
from the concentration camps
and just for those of you

00:29:49.850 --> 00:29:51.990
who don't know, so
the British had gotten

00:29:51.990 --> 00:29:56.600
into the war thinking it's going to
last a couple of months and, well,

00:29:56.600 --> 00:29:58.800
it started October, it
would be out by Christmas,

00:29:58.800 --> 00:30:00.710
and it ended up lasting
almost three years.

00:30:00.710 --> 00:30:03.300
And so by the end, they
were desperate to get out.

00:30:03.300 --> 00:30:05.720
And so they did some
pretty horrible things.

00:30:05.720 --> 00:30:09.050
They resorted to-- scorched
the earth policy and they set

00:30:09.050 --> 00:30:13.670
up these concentration camps for
as you say the women and children

00:30:13.670 --> 00:30:15.320
who were supporting
these men who were

00:30:15.320 --> 00:30:17.390
out fighting in the
field, the Boers.

00:30:17.390 --> 00:30:19.530
And so that they wouldn't
have any support.

00:30:19.530 --> 00:30:21.070
And it was disastrous.

00:30:21.070 --> 00:30:24.190
It was what-- And Native
Africans were also forced

00:30:24.190 --> 00:30:28.980
into concentration camps and even
more of them died in the Boers.

00:30:28.980 --> 00:30:32.330
Churchill on the other hand, his
imprisonment, the Boers were eager

00:30:32.330 --> 00:30:36.130
to show the British that
they were civilized too.

00:30:36.130 --> 00:30:39.190
The British had always sort
of dismissed them as sort

00:30:39.190 --> 00:30:41.010
of being backwards and rough.

00:30:41.010 --> 00:30:45.550
And so they allowed just
like incredible leniency.

00:30:45.550 --> 00:30:50.330
But Churchill couldn't stand
the idea of being captured.

00:30:50.330 --> 00:30:54.570
And in fact he said he hated
this period in his life more

00:30:54.570 --> 00:30:58.870
than he had ever hated any
other period in his whole life.

00:30:58.870 --> 00:31:01.700
And he was desperate to get out.

00:31:01.700 --> 00:31:03.170
And he remembered that.

00:31:03.170 --> 00:31:06.410
So, later on when he
gets into public life

00:31:06.410 --> 00:31:10.100
and he becomes home secretary,
it was one of his missions

00:31:10.100 --> 00:31:13.130
to show compassion to prisoners.

00:31:13.130 --> 00:31:18.210
And, you know, he made sure
that they had access to books,

00:31:18.210 --> 00:31:22.520
they had access to the outdoors,
that they could exercise.

00:31:22.520 --> 00:31:26.660
Because he said, you know,
whether or not they are guilty

00:31:26.660 --> 00:31:31.240
of some horrendous crime,
they are still human beings.

