00:36:52.250 --> 00:36:59.200
at why Theodore Roosevelt
was doing this.

00:36:59.200 --> 00:37:04.120
Aside, why do you believe-- what
was his motivation for doing it?

00:37:04.120 --> 00:37:06.580
I mean he's just-- I just--

00:37:06.580 --> 00:37:09.730
I don't want to give
you my own opinion but--

00:37:09.730 --> 00:37:11.030
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard:
Well, so for those of you

00:37:11.030 --> 00:37:13.050
who don't know the story,
so the-- Theodore Roosevelt,

00:37:13.050 --> 00:37:18.310
he lost the election of 1912 and
then he goes to South America

00:37:18.310 --> 00:37:20.030
and he goes down this incredibly,

00:37:20.030 --> 00:37:24.220
incredibly dangerous
rapids choked river

00:37:24.220 --> 00:37:26.110
that no one knows where it leads.

00:37:26.110 --> 00:37:30.250
That's why the man who found the
headwaters called it Rio da Duvida,

00:37:30.250 --> 00:37:34.400
the River of Doubt, and because
no one knew where it was going

00:37:34.400 --> 00:37:36.800
to take them and what
was around each bend.

00:37:36.800 --> 00:37:40.770
And the reason he did it was
because he was Theodore Roosevelt

00:37:40.770 --> 00:37:42.850
and Winston Churchill
would have done it too.

00:37:42.850 --> 00:37:47.880 position:56%
So he's a-- So, you know, he had won
and won and won throughout his life

00:37:47.880 --> 00:37:52.490
and then he loses, and he loses
this huge contest and he's a pariah

00:37:52.490 --> 00:37:54.540
for the first time in his life.

00:37:54.540 --> 00:37:57.960
He's put Woodrow Wilson, a
Democrat, in the White House

00:37:57.960 --> 00:37:59.380
because he split the
Republican vote.

00:37:59.380 --> 00:38:04.530
And he, you know, have this
depression that had sort

00:38:04.530 --> 00:38:06.310
of haunted him through his life.

00:38:06.310 --> 00:38:08.550
And he was devastated.

00:38:08.550 --> 00:38:14.040 position:56%
And so he gets this invitation to go
in a speaking tour in South America.

00:38:14.040 --> 00:38:16.980
He is this incredible
naturalist, has written many books

00:38:16.980 --> 00:38:19.830
about especially birds
and so he's going

00:38:19.830 --> 00:38:21.790
to take another collecting trip.

00:38:21.790 --> 00:38:24.480
He gets there and nobody
has been prepared.

00:38:24.480 --> 00:38:27.870
He let this, this friend
of his who was a priest

00:38:27.870 --> 00:38:33.200
who hired an arctic explorer to
plan this trip in the Amazon.

00:38:33.200 --> 00:38:36.410
And so they're not even prepared
for this-- a collecting trip.

00:38:36.410 --> 00:38:40.490
And he gets there and the foreign
minister says, you could do that,

00:38:40.490 --> 00:38:43.420
or you could map an unmapped river

00:38:43.420 --> 00:38:48.060
and Theodore Roosevelt is
going to say no to that?

00:38:48.060 --> 00:38:50.500
No. And so he throws himself
and the people with him

00:38:50.500 --> 00:38:54.780
into this outrageously
dangerous trip.

00:38:54.780 --> 00:38:56.080
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Yardley:
Just time for one more.

00:38:56.080 --> 00:38:57.380
Thank you.

00:38:57.380 --> 00:38:58.680
You're the lucky first.

00:38:58.680 --> 00:39:01.510
&gt;&gt; Can you talk a little bit about
how you reconstructed the events

00:39:01.510 --> 00:39:03.110
after President Garfield was shot,

00:39:03.110 --> 00:39:05.300
particularly the medical
care he received?

00:39:05.300 --> 00:39:08.970
And I find it so remarkable that
if the doctors had left him alone,

00:39:08.970 --> 00:39:11.190
he might very well lived.

00:39:11.190 --> 00:39:12.490
&gt;&gt; Candice Millard: Right.

00:39:12.490 --> 00:39:13.790
Yeah. He would have.

00:39:13.790 --> 00:39:16.020
So, again for those of you
who don't know, so the--

00:39:16.020 --> 00:39:20.140
So, Garfield was shot actually in a
train station that was on the mall.

00:39:20.140 --> 00:39:22.140
It's where the National
Gallery now sits.

00:39:22.140 --> 00:39:26.740
And to my outrage, there is
no plaque, no notice at all

00:39:26.740 --> 00:39:29.460
that an American president
was shot here.

00:39:29.460 --> 00:39:33.240
But the bullet that hit him, that
went in the right side of his back,

00:39:33.240 --> 00:39:37.060
it didn't hit any vital organs,
didn't hit his spinal cord.

00:39:37.060 --> 00:39:42.190
His injuries were far less severe
than Reagan's when Reagan was shot.

00:39:42.190 --> 00:39:45.620
And his-- But he had
twelve different doctors,

00:39:45.620 --> 00:39:50.330
especially this beautifully named
doctor, Doctor Willard Bliss,

00:39:50.330 --> 00:39:52.900
whose first name was Doctor,

00:39:52.900 --> 00:39:57.010 position:56%
who repeatedly inserted
unsterilized fingers and instruments

00:39:57.010 --> 00:40:02.000
in his back probing for this
bullet, even though Joseph Lister

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:06.330
of Listerine had discovered
antisepsis 16 years earlier

00:40:06.330 --> 00:40:09.460
and come here and spoke
to American doctors.

00:40:09.460 --> 00:40:13.760
And so it is sickening to watch
this, you know, through the lens

00:40:13.760 --> 00:40:20.040
of 135 years happening to
this extraordinary man.

00:40:20.040 --> 00:40:24.210
And so I went-- A lot of-- So I
did a ton of research obviously

00:40:24.210 --> 00:40:28.040
at the Library of Congress because
even though Garfield was president

00:40:28.040 --> 00:40:30.420
for a short time, he had been
in Congress for almost 18 years

00:40:30.420 --> 00:40:34.140
and his papers and a lot of the
people surrounding it were there.

00:40:34.140 --> 00:40:37.270
But also I went to the National
Museum of Health and Medicine

00:40:37.270 --> 00:40:42.110
and they actually have
the autopsy report there.

00:40:42.110 --> 00:40:44.310
But more than that, they have--

00:40:44.310 --> 00:40:49.200
I held in my gloved hand a
section of Churchill's-- Sorry.

00:40:49.200 --> 00:40:53.580
Garfield's spine with
this red plastic pin going

00:40:53.580 --> 00:40:56.030
through where the bullet
had gone through.

00:40:56.030 --> 00:40:58.360
And it's stunning.

00:40:58.360 --> 00:41:00.870
And they also have strangely there,

00:41:00.870 --> 00:41:03.690
they have what I called
the assassin's drawer

00:41:03.690 --> 00:41:09.020
because they have these-- they
have the remains of Charles Guiteau

00:41:09.020 --> 00:41:11.000
who assassinated Garfield.

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:12.300
And then they also have the remains

00:41:12.300 --> 00:41:15.060
of John Wilkes Booth kind
of in the same drawer.

00:41:15.060 --> 00:41:16.360
They have-- There is the femur,

00:41:16.360 --> 00:41:18.900
there is the ankle
bone, it's just bizarre.

00:41:18.900 --> 00:41:24.500
They also have a jar with
chunks of Guiteau's brain.

00:41:24.500 --> 00:41:29.910
And they-- He was insane
and he was mentally ill.

00:41:29.910 --> 00:41:33.940
And after he was executed, they
exhumed his body and they wanted

00:41:33.940 --> 00:41:36.910
to study it for science to
see, especially his brain,

00:41:36.910 --> 00:41:39.780
to see if you could see
physical signs of insanity.

00:41:39.780 --> 00:41:42.280
And so they cut up his brain
and they send it to experts

00:41:42.280 --> 00:41:45.870
around the country and they
send it back and said, well,

00:41:45.870 --> 00:41:48.540
he probably had syphilis
but that's all we can tell.

00:41:48.540 --> 00:41:52.130
And they put it in this
jar and they still have it.

00:41:52.130 --> 00:41:53.430
Thank you.

